The subjective experience of oneself and the outside environment, including perceptions, thoughts, emotions, and goals, is referred to as consciousness in biopsychology. It entails being conscious of one's environment, identity, and emotional emotions. Examining the exact neurological processes and brain activity that are connected to conscious experience is known as studying the "neural correlates of consciousness." This might include figuring out which particular brain areas and neural circuits are engaged during various conscious states and investigating how these neural processes produce the subjective experience of consciousness. Experimental studies of consciousness may be conducted using a variety of techniques, including neuroimaging, neuropsychology, and electrophysiology. Using these techniques, scientists may analyze the neural activity and brain areas connected to various conscious states, including perception, attention, and memory. The investigation of the neural correlates of visual awareness using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) is an example of a research on the brain processes underlying consciousness. This research may entail displaying visual stimuli to participants, such as pictures or patterns, while fMRI is used to track their brain activity. In order to pinpoint the precise brain areas and neural circuits connected to visual awareness, researchers may then contrast the brain activity of people who are aware of the visual stimuli with those who are not. Similar methods were used in a 2006 research by Tsuchiya and Koch to look into the neurological bases of visual awareness. A brain area known as the primary visual cortex (V1) was found to be more active when individuals reported being aware of the visuals when researchers used an fMRI to evaluate the brain activity of participants while they watched a fast stream of images. This work shows that fMRI may be used to investigate the neural correlates of consciousness and offers evidence for the function of V1 in visual awareness. 